{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d261d58e-7826-469d-8b1f-4d0e2adcf3f1","content":"The .NET MAUI Android build system **does not use `JAVA_HOME`** by default. It uses the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property, which typically points to the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the `android` workload.\n\n**Fix — tell MSBuild to use your Adoptium JDK:**\n\nOption 1: Pass it on the command line:\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=\"$JAVA_HOME\"\n```\n\nOption 2: Set it in your `.csproj` or `Directory.Build.props`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>$(JAVA_HOME)</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nAlso verify your `JAVA_HOME` ends with `/Contents/Home`:\n```bash\necho $JAVA_HOME\n# Should be: /Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```\n\n**Alternative fix** — install the workload-bundled JDK instead:\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui-android\n```\nThis installs Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 to the path the build already expects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5db36b92-3791-4167-9614-ee5257bc2975","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nThis is a common issue with .NET MAUI Android builds. The problem is that .NET MAUI / Android SDK has specific Java version requirements. Let me think about what's likely wrong:\n\n1. .NET 8 MAUI requires JDK 17, but there can be path issues on macOS\n2. The common issue on macOS is that JAVA_HOME needs to point to the correct path structure - specifically the `Contents/Home` subdirectory of the JDK installation\n\n\n3. On macOS, Adoptium Temurin typically installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, and JAVA_HOME needs to point to that exact location for the Android SDK to recognize it properly.\n\n4. The real culprit is often that .NET MAUI's Android build system uses the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property, which doesn't automatically respect JAVA_HOME environment variables—you typically need to set it explicitly in your project file or build configuration.\n\n5. In 2026, the most likely issue is version misalignment: .NET 9 MAUI requires JDK 17, and the Android Gradle plugin and build tools each have their own specific JDK version requirements that need to align.\n\n6. But the most common macOS-specific problem is that .NET MAUI's Android workload installs its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17, which can conflict with Adoptium Temurin if both are present—the build system might be pointing to the wrong JDK installation, or looking for it in an unexpected macOS directory path. I'm thinking through the most common Java-related errors in .NET MAUI Android builds—like `Could not determine java version` when the JDK isn't found, or `Unsupported class file major version` when there's a mismatch between the JDK version and what the build tools expect.\n\nSince the user has Temurin 17.0.12 installed and JAVA_HOME set correctly, the real issue is likely that the .NET Android build tooling on macOS doesn't always respect the JAVA_HOME environment variable—it has its own logic for finding the JDK, checking places like the Microsoft OpenJDK workload or `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/`. The solution would be to explicitly set the `JavaSdkDirectory` MSBuild property in the project file or pass it as a build parameter. The .NET MAUI Android build system doesn't actually use JAVA_HOME by default in newer versions—it relies on the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the Android workload instead. So even though the user has Adoptium Temurin 17 properly configured, the build system is looking elsewhere. The most practical solution is to explicitly point MSBuild to the JDK location...\n\nSetting the JavaSdkDirectory property... I'm realizing the most likely culprit here is that .NET 9/10 MAUI on Android needs JDK 17, and the build system looks for `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` which might not be pointing to the right location or format on macOS. The path needs to include `/Contents/Home` at the end when using Adoptium Temurin, otherwise the build tools can't find the Java compiler and related utilities it needs.","outputTokens":2570,"requestId":"E84C:16E90D:24F3A3D:2902447:69F93F2C"},"id":"9de87961-bb93-4b1c-a48e-a40ca4b12695","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:52:42.809Z","parentId":"fb8c1e70-6a93-463e-b19b-f9cbefb876ba"}
